	1. What is HTML?
	HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language.
	It is used to create and structure web pages.
	With HTML, we tell the browser what content to show, like headings, paragraphs, images, links, and forms.
	ðŸ‘‰ In simple words:
	HTML is used to build the basic structure of a website.
	
	
	2. What is the basic structure of an HTML document?
	The basic structure of an HTML document consists of four main parts:
		1. <!DOCTYPE html> â€“ tells the browser that the document is HTML5
		2. <html> â€“ the root element of the page
		3. <head> â€“ contains page information like title and meta data
		4. <body> â€“ contains the visible content of the webpage
	
	Simple Example:
	
	<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>My Web Page</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Hello World</h1>
    <p>This is my first webpage.</p>
</body>
</html>
	
	3. What is <!DOCTYPE html> and why is it used?
	<!DOCTYPE html> tells the browser that the document is written in HTML5.
	It helps the browser display the webpage correctly by following standard HTML rules.
	
	Why is it used? (Simple points)
		â€¢ It informs the browser about the HTML version
		â€¢ It prevents display errors
		â€¢ It ensures the page runs in standard mode
	
	4. What is the difference between HTML tags and elements?
	â€¢ HTML tags are used to define or mark the start and end of an element.
	â€¢ HTML elements include the start tag, content, and end tag.

Example:

<p>This is a paragraph</p>
	â€¢ <p> and </p> â†’ Tags
	â€¢ <p>This is a paragraph</p> â†’ Element

	1. What are attributes in HTML?
	Attributes provide extra information about HTML elements.
	They are written inside the opening tag and usually come in name = value format.
	Attributes tell the browser how an element should behave or look.
	
	Example:
	
	<a href="https://example.com">Visit</a>
		â€¢ href â†’ attribute name
		â€¢ "https://example.com" â†’ attribute value
	
	2. What are empty (void) elements?
	Empty or void elements are HTML elements that do not have any content and do not need a closing tag.
	They are used to perform a specific task on the webpage.
	
	Examples:
	
	<br>    <!-- line break -->
<hr>    <!-- horizontal line -->
<img>   <!-- image -->
<input> <!-- input field -->
	
	3. What is the difference between <div> and <span>?
	â€¢ <div> is a block-level element.
It starts on a new line and takes the full width of the page.
	â€¢ <span> is an inline element.
It stays in the same line and takes only the required space.

Example:

<div>This is a div</div>
<span>This is a span</span>

One-line interview answer:
	<div> is a block-level element used for grouping content, while <span> is an inline element used for styling small parts of text.


	
	1. What is the difference between <b> and <strong>?
	â€¢ <b> is used to make text bold only for appearance.
It does not add any importance.
	â€¢ <strong> is used to make text bold with importance.
It tells the browser and screen readers that the text is important.
	
	2. What is the <a> tag and how does it work?
	The <a> tag is used to create links (hyperlinks) in HTML.
	It connects one webpage to another or to a different part of the same page.
	It works using the href attribute, which contains the link address.
	
	Example:
	
	<a href="https://example.com">Visit Website</a>
	When the user clicks the link, the browser opens the page given in href.

	1. What is the difference between absolute and relative URLs?
	â€¢ Absolute URL contains the full address of a webpage, including protocol and domain name.
	â€¢ Relative URL contains a partial address and works based on the current page location.

Example:

<!-- Absolute URL -->
<a href="https://www.example.com/about.html">About</a>
<!-- Relative URL -->
<a href="about.html">About</a>


	1. What is the <img> tag and what is the use of alt attribute?
	The <img> tag is used to display images on a webpage.
	It does not have a closing tag and works using attributes.
	The alt attribute provides alternate text for an image.
	
	Why is alt important?
		â€¢ It shows text if the image does not load
		â€¢ It helps screen readers for visually impaired users
		â€¢ It improves SEO
	
	Example:
	
	<img src="logo.png" alt="Company Logo">

	1. What are the different types of lists in HTML?
	There are three types of lists in HTML:
		1. Ordered List (<ol>) â€“ shows items in numbered order
		2. Unordered List (<ul>) â€“ shows items with bullets
		3. Description List (<dl>) â€“ shows items with descriptions
	
	2. What is a table in HTML?
	A table in HTML is used to display data in rows and columns, like marks, employee details, or reports.
	It helps to show data in a structured and readable format.

	1. What is the difference between <tr>, <td>, and <th>?
	â€¢ <tr> (table row)
Used to create a row in a table.
	â€¢ <td> (table data)
Used to create normal data cells inside a row.
	â€¢ <th> (table header)
Used to create header cells.
Text inside <th> is bold and centered by default.

	1. What is rowspan and colspan?
	â€¢ rowspan is used to merge multiple rows into a single cell.
	â€¢ colspan is used to merge multiple columns into a single cell.
	
	2. What is a form in HTML?
	A form in HTML is used to collect user input such as name, email, password, or feedback.
	The data entered in a form is usually sent to a server for processing.
	
	3. What is the difference between GET and POST method?
	â€¢ GET method
		â€¢ Sends data in the URL
		â€¢ Less secure
		â€¢ Used for fetching data
		â€¢ Has data size limit
	â€¢ POST method
		â€¢ Sends data in the request body
		â€¢ More secure
		â€¢ Used for sending sensitive data
		â€¢ No size limit
	
	4. What are different types of <input> elements?
	<input> elements are used to take input from the user in a form.
	Some common types are:
		â€¢ text â€“ for normal text
		â€¢ password â€“ hides input text
		â€¢ email â€“ for email address
		â€¢ number â€“ for numbers
		â€¢ radio â€“ select one option
		â€¢ checkbox â€“ select multiple options
		â€¢ date â€“ pick a date
		â€¢ file â€“ upload a file
		â€¢ submit â€“ submit the form
		â€¢ reset â€“ reset the form
	
	5. What is the name attribute in forms?
	The name attribute is used to identify form fields.
	When a form is submitted, the data is sent to the server in name = value pairs.
	Without the name attribute, the input data will not be sent to the server.
	
	Example:
	
	<form>
  <input type="text" name="username">
  <input type="password" name="password">
</form>

	1. What is HTML5?
	HTML5 is the latest version of HTML used to create modern websites.
	It adds new tags and features that make websites more interactive, fast, and user-friendly, like audio, video, and semantic elements.
	
	2. What are semantic elements in HTML5?
	Semantic elements are HTML tags that clearly describe their meaning and purpose in the webpage.
	They make the code easy to understand for developers, browsers, and search engines.
	
	Examples of semantic elements:
	
	<header>, <footer>, <section>, <article>, <nav>
	
	.
	3. What is the difference between <div> and semantic tags?
	â€¢ <div> is a non-semantic tag.
It does not tell anything about the content inside it.
	â€¢ Semantic tags clearly describe the meaning of the content inside them, like header, footer, article, etc.
Semantic tags help in better SEO, readability, and accessibility.

Example:

<div>Header Content</div>
<header>Header Content</header>

	1. What is accessibility in HTML?
	Accessibility in HTML means creating web pages that everyone can use, including people with disabilities.
	It ensures that websites work well with screen readers, keyboard navigation, and other assistive technologies.
	
	Examples of accessibility:
		â€¢ Using alt text for images
		â€¢ Using proper semantic tags
		â€¢ Making forms readable and usable

	1. What is the viewport meta tag?
	The viewport meta tag is used to control how a webpage looks on different screen sizes, especially on mobile devices.
	It helps make websites responsive.
	
	Example:
	
	<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

	1. What is the difference between id and class?
	â€¢ id
		â—‹ Used for one unique element
		â—‹ Cannot be repeated on the same page
		â—‹ Written with # in CSS
	â€¢ class
		â—‹ Used for multiple elements
		â—‹ Can be reused many times
		â—‹ Written with . in CSS

Example:

<div id="header"></div>
<p class="text"></p>
<p class="text"></p>
	
	1. Is HTML case-sensitive?
	No, HTML is not case-sensitive.
	HTML tags and attributes work the same whether written in uppercase or lowercase.
	However, lowercase is recommended because it follows HTML standards and improves readability.
	
	2. How does HTML work with CSS and JavaScript?
	â€¢ HTML creates the structure of a webpage
	â€¢ CSS is used for styling the webpage (colors, layout, design)
	â€¢ JavaScript adds functionality and interactivity (buttons, validation, animations)
They work together to build a complete website.

Simple example:

<h1>Hello</h1>        <!-- HTML -->
<style>h1{color:red;}</style>   <!-- CSS -->
<script>alert("Hi");</script>   <!-- JavaScript -->
	
	
